00:56:17.000 --> 00:56:21.000
Maybe they were 10 miles. I don't know.

769
00:56:21.000 --> 00:56:28.000
But I do know they came in constant procession and I thought it would never end.

770
00:56:28.000 --> 00:56:34.000
What the Germans must have thought is beyond comprehension.

771
00:56:34.000 --> 00:56:39.000
The flight across the sky was slow and studied.

772
00:56:39.000 --> 00:56:50.000
I've never known a storm or a machine or any resolve of men that had about at the aura of such a ghastly relentnesses.

773
00:56:50.000 --> 00:57:01.000
I had the feeling that even had God appeared besiegingly before them in the sky with palms out stretched to persuade them back.

774
00:57:01.000 --> 00:57:10.000
They would not have had the power within them to turn from their irresistible course.

775
00:57:10.000 --> 00:57:20.000
This is just, that's such an incredible description of this impending doom.

776
00:57:20.000 --> 00:57:29.000
I stood with a little group of men ranging from kernels to privates back to the stone farmhouse.

777
00:57:29.000 --> 00:57:36.000
Slit trenches were all around the edges of the farm yard and a dugout with a tin roof was nearby.

778
00:57:36.000 --> 00:57:44.000
But we were so fascinated by the spectacle overhead that it never occurred to us that we might need the foxholes.

779
00:57:44.000 --> 00:57:50.000
The first huge flight passed directly overhead and others followed.

780
00:57:50.000 --> 00:57:57.000
We spread our feet and leaned far back trying to look straight up until our steel helmets fell off.

781
00:57:57.000 --> 00:58:04.000
We'd cop our fingers around our eyes like field glasses for a clear review.

782
00:58:04.000 --> 00:58:07.000
And then the bombs came.

