00:58:07.000 --> 00:58:19.000
They began like the crackle of popcorn and almost instantly swelled into a monstrous fury of noise that seemed surely to destroy all the world ahead of us.

784
00:58:19.000 --> 00:58:28.000
From then on, from an hour and a half that had in it the agonies of centuries the bombs came down.

785
00:58:28.000 --> 00:58:33.000
A wall of smoke and dust erected by them grew high in the sky.

786
00:58:33.000 --> 00:58:38.000
It filtered along the ground back through our orchards.

787
00:58:38.000 --> 00:58:42.000
It sifted around us and into our noses.

788
00:58:42.000 --> 00:58:46.000
The bright day grew slowly dark from it.

789
00:58:46.000 --> 00:58:50.000
By now everything was an indescribable culture of sounds.

790
00:58:50.000 --> 00:58:53.000
Individual noises did not exist.

791
00:58:53.000 --> 00:59:01.000
The thundering of the motors in the sky and the roar of bombs ahead filled all the space from noise on the earth.

792
00:59:01.000 --> 00:59:05.000
Our own heavy artillery was crashing all around us.

793
00:59:05.000 --> 00:59:07.000
Yet we could hardly hear it.

